      "author_association" : "MEMBER",
      "body" : "it's an improvement but still not fully clear as to what actually needs to be done to set up tor password authentication. to be clear:\r\n- bitcoind's `torpassword` takes the *unhashed* password\r\n- tor's configuration `HashedControlPassword` has a hashed password\r\nIIRC they have a command that can either hash a password for their configuration file, or generate a password and show both the actual and hashed password\r\n\r\nthe way that this is worded, it sounds like bitcoind's argument takes the hashes password too\r\n",
      "commit_id" : "a607e6e4b48d243e15dbaaa03b487383c22e96a8",
      "created_at" : "2018-10-31T17:12:29Z",
      "diff_hunk" : "@@ -110,8 +110,8 @@ are seen with `-debug=tor` they can be resolved by adding both the user running\n the user running bitcoind to the same group and setting permissions appropriately. On\n Debian-based systems the user running bitcoind can be added to the debian-tor group,\n which has the appropriate permissions. An alternative authentication method is the use\n-of the `-torpassword` flag and a `hash-password` which can be enabled and specified in\n-Tor configuration.\n+of the `-torpassword=hashpassword` option. The `hashpassword` can be enabled and specified in\n+Tor configuration under the `HashedControlPassword` option.",
